{"title_page": "Bob Lutz (tennis)", "text_new": "{{other people||Bob Lutz (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n|name                  = Bob Lutz\n|image                 = \n|country               = {{USA}}\n|residence             = \n|birth_date            = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1947|08|29}}\n|birth_place           = [[San Clemente, California|San Clemente]], California\n|height                = {{convert|5|ft|11|in|m}}\n|turnedpro             = 1970<small> (amateur tour from 1965)\n|retired               = 1982\n|plays                 = Right-handed (one-handed backhand)\n|careerprizemoney      = $1,165,276\n|tennishofyear         = \n|tennishofid           = \n|singlesrecord         = 405\u2013274 \n|singlestitles         = 9\n|highestsinglesranking = No. 7 (1972<small>, [[Bud Collins]]</small>)<ref name=\"TotalTennis2003\">Collins, Bud (2003). ''Total Tennis: The Ultimate Tennis Encyclopedia'', p. 917.</ref>\n|AustralianOpenresult  = SF ([[1971 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1971]])\n|FrenchOpenresult      = 4R ([[1971 French Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1971]])\n|Wimbledonresult       = QF ([[1969 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1969]])\n|USOpenresult          = 4R ([[1967 U.S. National Championships - Men's Singles|1967]], [[1971 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1971]], [[1972 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1972]], [[1978 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1978]], [[1982 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1982]])\n|Othertournaments      = yes\n|WCTFinalsresult       = F ([[1972 World Championship Tennis Winter Finals \u2013 Singles|1972</small> w]])\n|doublesrecord         = 494\u2013215\n|doublestitles         = 43\n|highestdoublesranking = No. 6 (April 30, 1977)\n|AustralianOpenDoublesresult = '''W''' (1970)\n|FrenchOpenDoublesresult     = F (1974)\n|WimbledonDoublesresult      = F (1974, 1980, 1981)\n|USOpenDoublesresult         = '''W''' (1968, 1974, 1978, 1980)\n}}\n\n'''Robert Lutz''' (born August 29, 1947) is a former amateur and professional [[tennis]] player of the 1960s and 1970s. He and his longtime partner [[Stan Smith]] were one of the best [[doubles (tennis)|doubles]] teams of all time. [[Bud Collins]] ranked Lutz as world No. 7 in 1972.<ref name=\"TotalTennis2003\"/> Between 1967 and 1977, he was ranked among the top-10 American players eight times, with his highest ranking being No. 5 in both 1968 and 1970.\n\n==Career==\nLutz won the 1967 [[NCAA Men's Tennis Championship#Singles|NCAA singles title]] and, partnering with [[Stan Smith]], won the [[NCAA Men's Tennis Championship#Doubles|NCAA doubles crown]] in 1967 and 1968.\n\nDuring his career he won nine singles titles, the most important being the [[1972 U.S. Pro Tennis Championships|U.S. Pro Tennis Championships]] in 1972 and the [[Paris Masters]] in 1978, and reached 15 other singles finals, including [[Cincinnati Masters|Cincinnati]] in 1974. He also won 43 doubles titles, 37 of which were won partnering Stan Smith, and reached 30 other doubles finals. With Smith he formed the only team to win the doubles title at U.S. Championships on four different surfaces (clay, grass, hard and indoor).<ref name=\"who\">{{cite book|editor1-last=Emery|editor1-first=David|title=Who's Who in International Tennis|date=1983|publisher=Sphere|location=London|isbn=9780722133200|page=74}}</ref> His doubles titles include the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] in 1980, 1978, 1974, and 1968, the [[Australian Open]] in 1970 and Cincinnati in 1969. In addition, he played on five winning [[Davis Cup]] teams between 1968 and 1981 and had a 14\u20132 record playing doubles.<ref>{{cite web |title=Davis Cup player profile |url=http://www.daviscup.com/en/players/player.aspx?id=800174362|publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]] (ITF)}}</ref> Lutz was nominated for the ITF Tennis Hall of Fame thanks to these achievements.<ref>{{cite web |title=International Tennis Hall Of Fame Announces Ballot Names For 2010 Induction |url=http://www.tennisgrandstand.com/archives/5069/comment-page-1/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006101407/http://www.tennisgrandstand.com/archives/5069/comment-page-1/ |archivedate=October 6, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Honors and personal life==\nHe was inducted into the Collegiate Tennis Hall of Fame in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|title=ITA Men's Hall of Fame|url=http://www.itatennis.com/AboutITA/HOF/Mens.htm|publisher=[[Intercollegiate Tennis Association]] (ITA)}}</ref> Lutz, a 1971 [[University of Southern California]] graduate, was inducted into their Hall of Fame in 2009.<ref name=\"ocr2009\">{{cite web|author1=Mark Garcia|title=San Clemente's Lutz to be inducted into tennis hall of fame|url=http://www.ocregister.com/2009/07/17/san-clementes-lutz-to-be-inducted-into-tennis-hall-of-fame/|website=[[The Orange County Register]]|date=July 17, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=USC Hall of Fame |url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/usc/genrel/auto_pdf/02hofbios.pdf}}</ref> He has been living in San Clemente since 1973 with his wife, Sharon, and their two daughters, Samantha and Allison.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tennis column: Q&A - Catching up with Bob Lutz|url=https://www.dcourier.com/news/2011/oct/13/tennis-column-qa-catching-up-with-bob-lutz/|website=[[The Daily Courier (Arizona)|The Daily Courier]]|date=October 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career finals==\n===Singles (9 titles, 15 runner-ups)===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!style=\"width:40px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:20px\" class=\"unsortable\"|No.\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Date\n!style=\"width:200px\"|Tournament\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:170px\"|Opponent\n!style=\"width:180px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss\n| 1.\n| 1968\n| U.S. Championships, Boston\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Arthur Ashe]]\n| 6\u20134, 3\u20136, 10\u20138, 0\u20136, 4\u20136\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| 1.\n| 1971\n| [[Central California Open National Har